The question itself was wrong!

  
    http://pics.livejournal.com/mudasobwa/pic/0002487g_*Mu*_ ( Japanese (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_language)  / Korean (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Korean_language)  ), and _*Wu*_ ( Chinese (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_language)   traditional:  無 (http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%84%A1)  , simplified:  无 (http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%97%A0)    pinyin (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinyin)  : _wú_  Jyutping (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jyutping)  : _mou2_), is a word which has been roughly translated as “no”, “none”, “null”, “without”, and “no meaning”.  
    The best-known _mu_ koan is as follows: A monk asked  Zhaozhou Congshen (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhaozhou_Congshen)  , a Chinese Zen master (known as _Jōshū_ in Japanese), "Has a dog  Buddha-nature (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddha-nature)   or not?" Zhaozhou answered, _"Wú"_ (in Japanese, _Mu_).

—  Mu (negative) (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mu_%28negative%29)  ,  Wikipedia (http://en.wikipedia.org/)   

Вах! Какое оружие в устах толерантного ритора!